  5. Plan9 Mastering Engineer

    Location:
    Toulouse, France
    Install Foobar, then install the "Effect DSP" component: foobar2000: Components Repository - Effect DSP
    In Foobar: File > Preferences > DSP manager > IIR filter > CD De-emphasis > apply. (everything played through this will have De-emph applied)
    Play the files. Voil!

  12. rnranimal Senior Member

    Location:
    Ohio
    ZenArcher said:
    Could you post that here for the rest of us?
    Click to expand...
    Sorry. I got home from work and then went drinking. Ok, here goes...

    The super simple Mac way is to download xACT. It has a de-emphasis filter under the "util" tab. As simple as loading the files in and hitting "execute".

    However, if you want some extra quality, you can do this first...

    Download XLD. Under "output format" select WAV. Then "options". Change bit depth to 32-bit and click "floating point". Drop your CD files (with pre-emphasis intact) onto the program and it will convert them to 32-bit floating. All it does is add blank bits for now. We just need to do this so that when xACT processes the files, it does so at 32-bit and saves them out that way. Once you have your 32-bit files now, you can do what I described above to de-emphasize them. After that, you have de-emphasized files at 32-bit. To end up with 24-bit files, simply change the XLD options to 24-bit and resave them. If you want 16-bit files, you will need to open them in other software which can dither. Also preferably you would increase gain if there is any decent amount of headroom left after the de-emphasis, before dithering.
     
    rnranimal, Jun 28, 2019

    Here is a ZIP containing WAV files and a cue sheet for making your own pre-emphasis test disc. Burn it using a program that supports burning a disc from a .CUE file, such as Exact Audio Copy:

    http://www.amstereo.org/files/pre-emph.zip

    Track listing:
    1. 20-20 kHz sine wave sweep (flat)
    2. 20-20 kHz sine wave sweep (with pre-emphasis)
    3. Music test (flat)
    4. Music test (with pre-emphasis)

    It also contains CD Text so you can also use it to test if your player supports that.

    Click to expand...
    The exact decimal values for Peak and RMS aren't important. The values can change due to different offsets for different pressings of the CD. Especially on a CD like DSOTM where the tracks are gapless. Change the offset and a few samples from the end of one song now become the beginning of the next song. And that can end up changing the Peak values.

    The exact values for DR for each track can also change by plus or minus one due to rounding when calculating DR. For example, JRiver Media Center is able to calculate DR values but can sometimes be off by one from the values calculated by the Foobar plugin. The Foobar plugin is the standard and the DR number(s) that should be compared against. Comparing DR numbers from Foobar against DR numbers calculated by a different program or tool can sometimes be off by one. Which is just due to rounding errors and the way computers do math.
     
    Ham Sandwich, Jun 28, 2019

  17. vwestlife Forum Resident

    MrRom92 said:
    Out of curiosity, why is it that EAC had to have the pre-emphasis detection removed but cuetools was able to retain it? Makes the workflow more difficult when theres a disc I suspect has PE, and there are bound to be a few missed ones that I was totally unaware of
    Click to expand...
    The current version of EAC (1.3 from 2016) can still detect pre-emphasis as long as it is flagged in the disc's Table Of Contents. Only the ability to manually detect pre-emphasis from the disc's subcode was removed:

    Exact Audio Copy - Hydrogenaudio Knowledgebase

    "EAC 0.9 beta 1 (21 Jan 2001) through 0.95 prebeta 3 (11 May 2003) had manual TOC detection as an option, useful if a CD is defective and displays wrong track positions or data tracks instead of audio; EAC will try to detect the CD structure by analysis. This could also be used to detect pre-emphasis and copyright flags in the subcode, since they're sometimes missing from the TOC. The manual TOC detection feature was removed in 0.95 prebeta 4 (9 Nov 2003) due to European legislation which would outlaw software capable of circumventing a certain type of CD copy protection involving erroneous TOC data."
     
    vwestlife, Jul 17, 2019

    rnranimal said:
    Sorry. I got home from work and then went drinking. Ok, here goes...

    The super simple Mac way is to download xACT. It has a de-emphasis filter under the "util" tab. As simple as loading the files in and hitting "execute".

    However, if you want some extra quality, you can do this first...

    Download XLD. Under "output format" select WAV. Then "options". Change bit depth to 32-bit and click "floating point". Drop your CD files (with pre-emphasis intact) onto the program and it will convert them to 32-bit floating. All it does is add blank bits for now. We just need to do this so that when xACT processes the files, it does so at 32-bit and saves them out that way. Once you have your 32-bit files now, you can do what I described above to de-emphasize them. After that, you have de-emphasized files at 32-bit. To end up with 24-bit files, simply change the XLD options to 24-bit and resave them. If you want 16-bit files, you will need to open them in other software which can dither. Also preferably you would increase gain if there is any decent amount of headroom left after the de-emphasis, before dithering.
    Click to expand...

  2. rnranimal Senior Member

    Location:
    Ohio
    Leviathan said:
    I followed these steps and take the 32-bit files and use XLD to convert it to 24-bit and save to my iTunes library. Now if I copy the files to my phone or portable music player will the files play without the pre-emphasis?
    Click to expand...
    As long as they were de-emphasized in XACT then they will be de-emphasized on your phone or anywhere else as the actual audio is altered in this method rather than having the playback device handle it (which isn't even an option with a lot of devices now).

    To make sure, load your original file into iTunes along with the new 24-bit file and listen to each. You should hear a clear difference in the high end and your 24-bit file should be noticeably less bright. If they sound the same, then it wasn't properly de-emphasized.

    Just to be clear, my method is for processing files which still have pre-emphasis intact. If you ripped the CD using iTunes, then it will have de-emphasized the tracks already (although, imo, a lower quality method). If these tracks were ripped by XLD from the CD, you're good.

  4. Ham Sandwich Forum Resident

    Location:
    Sherwood, OR, USA
    Leviathan said:
    Yes, the de-empasized tracks sound less bright, but they are also quieter. Is that normal? (The disc in question is the Dark Side of the Moon)
    Click to expand...
    The de-emphasized tracks will sound quieter. Because the EQ curve to apply de-emphasis cuts frequencies (starting at about 500 Hz up to -10 dB at 20 kHz). Since de-emphasis is an EQ cut it will have less overall energy and sound quieter. However, the de-emphasis EQ is flat to around 500 Hz. So if you listen to just the bass below 500 Hz the bass should be at the same level and loudness.

    Here's the EQ curve for what pre-emphasis adds and what de-emphasis cuts. When you combine the two you get a flat EQ. When you do de-emphasis to a CD that has pre-emphasis the result should sound like a flat EQ.

  10. harby Forum Resident

    Location:
    Portland, OR, USA
    Front 242 Addict said:
    Those who invented the pre-Emphasis must be arrested immediately

    pre-Emphasis in the Toc,not in the Toc, oh dear

    I tried to read the article you sent me about the differences,I think I can say that there is more chance of alien invasion tomorrow than the chance that I will understand the explanations LOL
    Click to expand...
    Quantization noise in old ADCs manifests as high-frequency noise, as the noise floor of the input signal is naturally "noise shaped" by the input signal noise, if not from analog devices that could barely manage 90dB of SNR, from the noise of analog recordings. Preemphasis diminishes the quantization noise below audibility. It makes for better encoding on ADCs with inaccurate last bits, or even 14 bits.

    ADC jitter acts as high-frequency quantization noise. With 350ms jitter, there is more jitter-based quantization noise above 9kHz then natural quantization possible from the 44.1/16. Pre-emphasis boosts high-frequency input, which when decoded, also reduces the effects of jitter.

    I've checked with the relevant authorities, and it seems it is past the statute of limitations to bring forth either criminal proceedings or civil action against the responsible parties.

  17. RockAddict Forum Resident

    Location:
    UK
    Bumped as I've just used Foobar to de-emphasis a CD rip.

    I won't pretend to have even close to the technical know-how of some of the posters in this thread and with that relative lack of tech knowledge, I thought this *might* be useful.

    Background: I have a handful of CDs that play super bright, including the album "Transition" by John Miles Band [2010 remaster] which contains a track that appears in one of many compilations I've put together. Every time that track played (until now!), it positively shrieked and was a truly unpleasant listen. I have no idea whether this is due to actual pre-emphasis or just a terrible master.

    In EAC, the pre-emphasis flag for the JM song ("Blinded") is "no" but, having read this thread and others on pre-emphasis, I learnt that a) the EAC flag isn't 100% reliable and, b) using de-emphasis on overly bright recordings that don't have pre-emphasis can (sometimes) provide a more than decent outcome.

    With that in mind, my search for a relatively simple solution began. Foobar + the following component (as at Apr 2020):
    foobar2000: Components Repository - De-emphasis postprocessor [v 0.2 at time of posting]

    Install the component as instructed.

    How to use when ripping a CD you want to use the de-emphasis component (whether or not the source CD has pre-emphasis):

    - insert CD
    - open Foobar (v 1.5.3 at the time of posting)
    - menu... File > Open audio CD > choose "Rip" > choose "Proceed to the Converter Setup dialog" > choose "Processing"

    After choosing "Processing", a dialog box opens. Insofar as is relevant to pre-emphasis / de-emphasis, look about half way down the dialog box and there are two colums / lists. In the right hand list, amongst other things, there should be a listing for "RIAA CD demphasis filter". Click on the "+" button next to it and the filter should now appear in the left hand list. Then:

    > Back > Convert > Select Folder etc.... [just normal saving routine from this point]

    There are several other settings not related specifically to de-emphasis but you'll have to figure those out yourself. If anyone sees anything in this post that needs clarifying or amending, go ahead - this is intended to add constructively to the info already given and I definitely won't take offence !

    The outcome for JM's "Blinded"? I did an A/B with a normal rip vs rip using the Foobar de-emphasis component. The latter is much nicer to listen to.


    Edited to add: the filter will need to be removed (in the "Processing" dialog box) if not wanted for other CD rips.
     
    Last edited: Apr 26, 2020
    RockAddict, Apr 26, 2020

    There are several other settings not related specifically to de-emphasis but you'll have to figure those out yourself. If anyone sees anything in this post that needs clarifying or amending, go ahead - this is intended to add constructively to the info already given and I definitely won't take offence !

    The outcome for JM's "Blinded"? I did an A/B with a normal rip vs rip using the Foobar de-emphasis component. The latter is much nicer to listen to.


    Edited to add: the filter will need to be removed (in the "Processing" dialog box) if not wanted for other CD rips.

    Wow, this is a nice, informative thread about PE/DE! And still open for postings, unlike most others.

    RockAddict said:
    In EAC, the pre-emphasis flag for the JM song ("Blinded") is "no" but, having read this thread and others on pre-emphasis, I learnt that a) the EAC flag isn't 100% reliable and, b) using de-emphasis on overly bright recordings that don't have pre-emphasis can (sometimes) provide a more than decent outcome.
    Click to expand...
    Plan9 said:
    However Pre-Emphasis is a thing from the early 1980s, a remaster from 2010 would not have it. It's just terrible mastering.
    Click to expand...
    Exactly.

    And I strongly doubt that de-emphasizing a non-pre-emphasized-but-brightly-mastered CD is a good method to 'fix' it. Granted, it may improve its sound because, yes, it will remove some brightness. However, de-emphasis filters are specifically designed to decode pre-emphasized CDs, and in my understanding, CDs with pre-emphasis do not merely sound bright, but also sound 'odd' or 'off' in other ways. Accordingly, a de-emphasis filter applied to a non-pre-emphasized-but-bright mastering will not just remove brightness, but also do other things that may easily be counterproductive. A CD that is just mastered bright is best 'fixed' by EQing it specifically in the way that makes it sound more pleasant to one's ears, not by running a filter that was designed to solve a very different problem.
     
    blacksabbathrainbow, Jun 20, 2020
    #76

  3. Plan9 Mastering Engineer

    Location:
    Toulouse, France
    motionoftheocean said:
    something I've always meant to ask...

    in the IIR DSP, there's a text field called "Q" - what does that mean and what should be entered in there?
    Click to expand...
    On an equalizer, the Q value affects the bandwidth of frequencies that will be boosted or cut. The lower the Q, the broader the bandwidth curve of frequencies that will be changed. A higher Q will affect a narrower bandwidth.
     
    Plan9, Sep 5, 2020
    #78
